## Playbook Depth Signal

Every step below cites the specific playbook note and rule that justifies it.
The primary reference is `coding-playbook/client/seo.md`, whose named
conventions define the rubric:

- `generateMetadata` / static `metadata` with title, description, openGraph,
  twitter (seo.md §generateMetadata)
- `alternates.canonical` in metadata for server-rendered canonical tags
  (seo.md §Canonical Tags — server-rendered branch)
- JSON-LD `Organization` + `WebSite` in root layout; page-specific schemas in
  page components (seo.md §Schema.org Structured Data)
- `sitemap.ts` with `lastModified` per entry (seo.md §Sitemap & Robots)
- Semantic HTML: `<header>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<section>`, `<article>`,
  `<aside>`, `<footer>` with appropriate roles (seo.md §Semantic HTML +
  Element Usage Guide)
- ARIA: `aria-label` on every `<section>`, `<nav>`, and icon-only interactive
  element (seo.md §ARIA Rules)

Where the playbook is silent (skip-link, color contrast ratios, keyboard
handlers on clickable `<div>`s, screen-reader announcements on animated
headlines, `aria-current` on active nav), the rubric falls back to WCAG 2.1
AA — justified by the root intent's Lighthouse ≥95 outcome in all four
categories, which cannot be reached without WCAG-AA hygiene. See
`## Decisions` for the full list of fallback rules and the intent line each
traces to.

## Plan

### 1. Promote marketing section titles to real headings.

Read: `coding-playbook/client/seo.md` (Semantic HTML + ARIA Rules),
`coding-playbook/foundations/conventions.md` (orchestrator/helper pattern)

- [x] 1a. Modify `src/app/_components/SectionHeader/index.tsx`: change the
  title `<span>` to an `<h2>`, keeping the `§{num}` accent prefix as a sibling
  `<span aria-hidden="true">` inside the heading. No visual change — same font
  size, weight, tracking, and baseline alignment. This gives the seven
  marketing sections that currently render `SectionHeader` a real heading
  each, bringing the marketing page's heading outline from
  `H1 → (span) (span) (span) (span) (span) (span) (span) H2` to
  `H1 → H2 H2 H2 H2 H2 H2 H2 H2`.
- [x] 1b. Verify `src/app/_components/Quickstart/index.tsx` still renders
  correctly — it imports `SectionHeader`, so it inherits the `<h2>` upgrade
  without code change. If the Quickstart layout breaks visually from the
  heading's default block margin, reset via inline `margin:0` on the heading
  element inside `SectionHeader` itself — do not touch the Quickstart file.
- [x] 1c. Verify `src/app/_components/Comparison/index.tsx` — it already uses
  its own `<h2>` ("Heavier. More opinionated. More hands-off."). No change
  needed. After §1 completes, every marketing `<section>` under `<main>`
  has exactly one `<h2>`, which is the semantic-HTML expectation in seo.md.

### 2. Promote docs category labels and sidebar section labels to headings.

Read: `coding-playbook/client/seo.md` (Semantic HTML + ARIA Rules)

- [x] 2a. Modify `src/app/docs/page.tsx`: each mapped category currently
  renders a `<section>` containing a `<div>` with `# {label}` and a list of
  `DocsIndexCard`s. Change the label `<div>` to an `<h2>` with the same
  visual styling, and give the outer `<section>` an `aria-label={label}`.
  The `/docs/` page outline becomes `H1 → H2 (METHODOLOGY) → H2 (COMMANDS)
  → H2 (AGENTS) → H2 (SKILLS)`.
- [x] 2b. Modify `src/app/docs/_components/DocsSidebar/SidebarShell/index.tsx`:
  change each per-category label `<div>` (`# {label}`) to an `<h2>` with
  equivalent styling. Add `aria-label="Documentation"` to the `<aside>` so
  it exposes an accessible name in the screen-reader landmark list.
- [x] 2c. In the same `SidebarShell/index.tsx`, collapse the four per-category
  `<nav>` elements into one outer `<nav aria-label="Documentation sections">`
  that wraps every SidebarRow map. Keep each category's `<h2>` as a child of
  the single `<nav>`. Rationale: four unnamed `<nav>` landmarks clutter
  AT-landmark menus; seo.md's ARIA Rules expect `<nav>` to be labelled and
  singular per meaningful group.
- [x] 2d. Mirror the same changes in
  `src/app/docs/_components/DocsSidebarDrawer/index.tsx` — same `<h2>` label
  change, same single labelled `<nav>`. The drawer uses `role="dialog"`
  not `<aside>`; keep the dialog role and add `aria-labelledby` pointing at
  the header's existing "aidemd.dev — docs" span (give that span an `id`
  like `docs-drawer-title`), giving the dialog an accessible name.

### 3. Mark active nav rows with aria-current="page".

Read: `coding-playbook/client/seo.md` (ARIA Rules)

- [x] 3a. In `src/app/docs/_components/DocsSidebar/SidebarShell/index.tsx`,
  add `aria-current={isActive ? 'page' : undefined}` to each `<Link>` in the
  SidebarRow map. The `isActive` value is already derived from `currentKey`;
  this step only wires it to ARIA.
- [x] 3b. In `src/app/docs/_components/DocsSidebarDrawer/index.tsx`, apply
  the same `aria-current` logic on the mobile drawer links.
- [x] 3c. In `src/app/_components/TopBar/index.tsx`, add `aria-current="page"`
  to the active top-bar nav link (the `isActive` branch of the `NAV_LINKS`
  map). Outbound `github ↗` and `npm ↗` anchors keep no `aria-current`.

### 4. Make IntentTree nodes keyboard-accessible.

Read: `coding-playbook/client/seo.md` (ARIA Rules — interactive elements),
`coding-playbook/foundations/conventions.md` (naming and helper decomposition)

- [x] 4a. Modify `src/app/_components/IntentTree/TreeNode/index.tsx`: when
  `isClickable` is true, the clickable `<div>` must expose a button role,
  be focusable, and respond to Enter / Space. Add `role="button"`,
  `tabIndex={0}`, `aria-expanded={open}` (only when `hasChildren` is true so
  non-expanding code/intent leaves don't falsely advertise collapsibility),
  and an `onKeyDown` handler that calls `handleClick` when `event.key` is
  `Enter` or `' '`. The existing `cursor: 'pointer'` and hover treatment
  stay. The `aria-expanded` value updates as `open` toggles, satisfying
  both seo.md's "interactive element gets an accessible name and state" rule
  and WCAG 2.1.1 Keyboard.

### 5. Fix VaultBrain file-list items: remove fake interactivity.

Read: `coding-playbook/client/seo.md` (Semantic HTML — interactive vs
decorative elements; `role="list"` only when native list element is not used)

- [x] 5a. Modify `src/app/_components/VaultBrain/index.tsx`: the left-pane
  `<div>` items currently set `cursor: 'pointer'` and hover-border tint but
  have no click handler — they promise interactivity they don't deliver.
  Strip `cursor: pointer`, `onMouseEnter`, `onMouseLeave`, and the
  border-left transition from each file item so the items read as static
  list content. Wrap the file list in a native `<ul>` and render each item
  as an `<li>`. Do not add `role="list"` — `<ul>` already carries list
  semantics; `role="list"` is only for custom list layouts per seo.md.
  Rationale: seo.md's semantic-HTML rule treats decorative affordances on
  non-interactive elements as drift.

### 6. Raise contrast on dim text tokens used for body copy.

Read: `coding-playbook/client/seo.md` (Semantic HTML — implicit in WCAG AA
baseline for Lighthouse ≥95)

- [x] 6a. In `src/app/globals.css` `@theme` block, add a new token
  `--color-dim-text: rgba(232, 223, 206, 0.72)`. Computed against `#0d0b08`
  this reaches ≥4.5:1 for normal body text. Keep `--color-dim` and
  `--color-dim-2` available for decorative use (borders, hairlines, dots,
  separator glyphs) so the Terminal handoff palette stays intact.
- [x] 6b. Sweep text-bearing usages of `--color-dim-2` and `--color-dim`
  at ≤13px font size in: `src/app/_components/Footer/index.tsx` (copyright
  line), `src/app/docs/_components/DocsFooter/index.tsx`,
  `src/app/docs/_components/DocsTemplate/Breadcrumb/index.tsx` (the segment
  text, not the `/` separators),
  `src/app/docs/_components/DocsIndexCard/index.tsx` (preview text and
  index numeral), `src/app/docs/_components/DocsTemplate/PrevNext/index.tsx`
  (← prev / next → direction labels),
  `src/components/DocMeta/index.tsx` (field labels),
  `src/app/docs/_components/DocsSidebar/SidebarShell/index.tsx` (row
  numeral). Swap each to `color: var(--color-dim-text)`. Leave decorative
  `--color-dim-2` uses (backdrop separators, traffic-light border tints,
  callout body outline) untouched.

### 7. Fix Typewriter's screen-reader spam.

Read: `coding-playbook/client/seo.md` (ARIA Rules — live regions)

- [x] 7a. Modify `src/app/_components/Hero/Typewriter/index.tsx`: remove
  `aria-live="polite"` and `aria-label={text}` from the visible animated
  overlay. The overlay updates roughly every 40ms during typing; with
  aria-live polite, assistive tech re-announces the heading on every
  character tick. Replace that pattern with a single static
  screen-reader-only exposure of the final text via a sibling
  `<span className="sr-only">{text}</span>`, and mark the visible animated
  overlay `aria-hidden="true"`. Add a standard `.sr-only` rule in
  `src/app/globals.css` using the clip-path hidden idiom. The existing
  invisible reserve span (currently `visibility: hidden; aria-hidden=true`)
  stays — it serves CLS, not SR.

### 8. Add server-rendered canonical + ship JSON-LD from root layout.

Read: `coding-playbook/client/seo.md` (Canonical Tags, Schema.org Structured
Data — Root Layout section)

- [x] 8a. Modify `src/app/layout.tsx`'s `metadata` export: add
  `alternates: { canonical: "https://aidemd.dev/" }`. This emits the
  canonical tag into the SSR HTML on every route that does not override
  `alternates`, which right now is the root `/`. Non-JS crawlers will then
  observe the canonical immediately instead of waiting for a hydration
  effect that never runs.
- [x] 8b. In the same file, move the `orgSchema` and `websiteSchema` JSON-LD
  blocks from `src/app/page.tsx` into `RootLayout`'s `<body>` as
  `<script type="application/ld+json" id="ld-org">` and
  `<script type="application/ld+json" id="ld-website">`. seo.md places
  Organization + WebSite schemas in the root layout because they apply to
  every route, not just the marketing page; shipping them only from `/`
  leaves 34 other routes without identity-graph coverage.
- [x] 8c. Delete both `<script>` blocks and the two schema consts from
  `src/app/page.tsx`. The marketing-page layout keeps its semantic structure
  but no longer injects Organization + WebSite schemas (now global).
- [x] 8d. Remove `src/components/CanonicalTag/index.tsx` (and its import
  from `src/app/layout.tsx`). With `alternates.canonical` in every route's
  metadata (marketing root just added, docs routes already have it), the
  client-side effect is redundant and only fired on `/` anyway. Removing it
  eliminates one client-only component from the root tree.

### 9. Use frontmatter description and add TechArticle JSON-LD on docs leaves.

Read: `coding-playbook/client/seo.md` (generateMetadata, Schema.org Structured
Data — Per-Page Schemas)

- [x] 9a. Modify `src/app/docs/[section]/[...slug]/page.tsx`'s
  `generateMetadata`: read `frontmatter` via `parseDocFrontmatter` following
  the pattern already in `src/app/docs/page.tsx`. Prefer
  `frontmatter.description` as the metadata description when present; fall
  back to the current `${route.title} — AIDE canonical documentation` only
  when no frontmatter description exists. Rationale: shipping 33 near-
  identical descriptions harms search ranking and the "canonical public
  face" positioning named in the root intent.
- [x] 9b. In the same `generateMetadata`, add an `openGraph` block with
  `type: 'article'`, `publishedTime: published`, and
  `modifiedTime: published`. The `published` field is already resolved by
  `renderDoc` in `src/service/docsRegistry` (the page's default export
  reads it from `renderDoc`); lift the resolution earlier in
  `generateMetadata` so both the metadata and the page component read the
  same value. `openGraph.images` and `twitter.card` remain inherited from
  the root layout — the `src/service/socialShare/.aide` spec explicitly
  documents that contract.
- [x] 9c. In the default-exported `DocLeafPage` in the same file, emit a
  per-route TechArticle JSON-LD `<script type="application/ld+json">`
  before the returned `<DocsTemplate>`. Fields: `@context:
  "https://schema.org"`, `@type: "TechArticle"`, `headline: route.title`,
  `datePublished: published`, `dateModified: published`, `author: { "@type":
  "Organization", name: "TetsuKodai Group LLC" }`, `isPartOf: { "@type":
  "WebSite", url: "https://aidemd.dev" }`, `mainEntityOfPage:
  "https://aidemd.dev${route.urlPath}"`. This matches seo.md's per-page
  JSON-LD pattern (AboutPage example shape, adapted to TechArticle). Emit
  from the page component so the section-index pages stay unmarked.
- [x] 9d. Verify `src/app/docs/[section]/page.tsx` already uses
  `SECTION_INDEX_META[section].lede` for metadata description — no change
  needed. Do NOT emit JSON-LD on section-index pages; those are navigation,
  not articles.

### 10. Build the /privacy route so existing footer anchors resolve.

Read: `coding-playbook/client/seo.md` (generateMetadata, Canonical Tags,
Semantic HTML), `coding-playbook/foundations/conventions.md` (file
structure for app-router routes). Root `intent.aide` `## Context` names
GA4 tracking with a production measurement ID; tracking users creates a
legal obligation for a published privacy policy, which both footer
anchors already advertise.

- [x] 10a. Create the route at `src/app/privacy/page.tsx` following the
  app-router static-export conventions used by the other marketing
  routes in this project. The file must export a named `metadata: Metadata`
  with:
    - `title: "Privacy Policy — aidemd.dev"`
    - `description`: one concise sentence, engineering-credible and
      precise (target audience: skeptical technical leads). Something
      along the lines of: what data the site collects and what it does
      not. Keep it one sentence.
    - `alternates: { canonical: "https://aidemd.dev/privacy" }`
    - `openGraph` and `twitter` inherit from root layout (do not
      override images or card)
    - `robots`: indexable — do NOT set `noindex`. The page is public.

    Default-export a `PrivacyPage` component that renders, in this
    order:
    - A `<a href="#main" className="skip-link">Skip to main content</a>`
      as the first element (matches §11 pattern on every other route).
      The `.skip-link` CSS rule is added in §11a; the final refactor
      state has both — order §10 before §11 is fine for final state,
      and §11 does not need to add another skip-link to this new page
      because §10a renders it.
    - The marketing `TopBar` (not the docs `ActiveAwareTopBar` — see
      `## Decisions` → "Visual template choice" for why).
    - A `<main id="main">` containing exactly one `<h1>Privacy Policy</h1>`
      followed by the policy body. Body content must cover, in any
      clean order the implementor picks:
        - **What is tracked.** GA4 page views only. Standard GA4
          cookies. No form inputs are collected (the site has no
          forms). No PII beyond what GA4 collects by default (IP is
          truncated by GA4, device/browser metadata, referrer, page
          path).
        - **Do Not Track.** DNT is honored — if the visitor's browser
          signals DNT, no GA4 hit fires.
        - **No ad/retargeting pixels.** No Meta pixel, no LinkedIn
          Insight tag, no third-party ad network beacons.
        - **Data controller.** TetsuKodai Group LLC (same entity that
          appears in the footer copyright). No other processors beyond
          Google Analytics.
        - **Contact.** The project's GitHub repository at
          `https://github.com/aidemd-mcp/server` is the contact
          channel — consistent with the root intent `## Strategy`
          line: "The GitHub link doubles as the 'contact' channel
          for v1."
        - **Last updated.** A visible "Last updated" date. Emit the
          build-time date as an ISO string via a static constant —
          do NOT call `new Date()` at runtime, and do NOT use the
          "2026-04-24" value literally in code; instead have the
          implementor pin a constant they can update on each deploy.
          Render the date inside a `<time dateTime="...">` element for
          semantic correctness.
    - The marketing `Footer` (not `DocsFooter` — matches the template
      choice above).

    Tone rules for the body prose: engineering-credible, precise,
    specific. No legalese padding, no "we may from time to time…"
    hedging, no marketing language. Short declarative sentences.
    Audience is a technical lead reading it in 30 seconds to decide
    whether to trust the project.

    Do NOT add any new helper folders under `privacy/` — this is a
    single-file leaf route. No JSON-LD emission is required on this
    route; inheritance from root layout (§8) covers Organization +
    WebSite.

- [x] 10b. Add the new `/privacy` URL to
  `src/app/sitemap.ts` as a sitemap entry alongside the marketing root,
  the `/docs/` index, and the section indexes. `lastModified` should
  match the "Last updated" constant rendered on the page (import it
  from `privacy/page.tsx` or redeclare the same constant in the
  sitemap — implementor picks; keep them in sync). The entry is
  indexable and appears in the public sitemap. Do NOT add it to
  `public/robots.txt` — no disallow needed.

  Leave both `<a href="/privacy">` anchors in
  `src/app/_components/Footer/index.tsx` and
  `src/app/docs/_components/DocsFooter/index.tsx` unchanged — they
  now resolve to the real route created in 10a.

### 11. Add a skip-to-main link for keyboard users.

Read: `coding-playbook/client/seo.md` (Semantic HTML, implied by Lighthouse
≥95 and WCAG 2.4.1 Bypass Blocks)

