## Decisions

### Playbook depth finding

The coding playbook has exactly one on-page SEO note:
`coding-playbook/client/seo.md`. It covers `generateMetadata`,
`generateStaticParams`, Schema.org JSON-LD (Organization + WebSite in the
root layout, page-specific schemas in page components), canonical tags
(client-side effect OR `alternates.canonical`), sitemap + robots, a
complete semantic-HTML element guide, and an ARIA rules list (`aria-label`
on every `<section>` / `<nav>` / interactive icon, `role="list"` on custom
list layouts, `autoComplete` on form inputs). That is the full depth the
playbook mandates, and this plan audits exactly against that rubric.

The playbook does NOT explicitly mandate:

1. Skip-to-main links
2. Color contrast ratios (WCAG AA)
3. Keyboard handlers on clickable `<div>`s
4. `aria-live` hygiene on animated content
5. `aria-current` on active nav
6. `themeColor` metadata
7. `lastModified` on sitemap entries
8. TechArticle JSON-LD on docs-style routes
9. Noindex metadata on 404s
10. Escape-key handling on `role="dialog"` elements

Items 1–4 are WCAG 2.1 AA requirements. The Lighthouse ≥95 outcome in the
root intent (`outcomes.desired`, the Lighthouse gate line) cannot be reached
without AA hygiene — Lighthouse's accessibility category is effectively a
WCAG-AA rollup — so those steps trace to the intent via the Lighthouse
gate, not the playbook directly.

Items 5–10 are standard W3C and Google Search Central guidance. The
"canonical public face of AIDE" positioning in the intent
(`outcomes.desired[0]`, `## Context`, `## Strategy`) implicitly requires
them — a site claiming to be the authoritative methodology reference that
omits noindex on its 404, lastModified on its sitemap, article schema on
its docs, and Escape-close on its dialog reads as unpolished to the
engineering-lead audience the intent names.

All ten items are flagged for potential **playbook gap**: if the
maintainers agree these are non-negotiable across future projects, seo.md
should be extended with a "WCAG-AA / Lighthouse-95 baseline" section
covering them explicitly. That change is not in this plan — the user has
queued it as a separate post-refactor task that fires after this plan
lands.

### Privacy route is in scope

The initial plan proposed removing both footer `/privacy` anchors on the
grounds that no such route existed. On user review, the direction was
reversed: the root `intent.aide` `## Context` documents that **GA4
page-view analytics are wired into the static export with a production
measurement ID**. Tracking users — even with IP truncation and DNT
honored — creates a legal obligation to publish a privacy policy. The
footer anchors already advertise the policy; removing them would hide
the obligation rather than resolve it. §10 therefore **builds the
`/privacy` route** and leaves the existing anchors untouched.

**Visual template choice: marketing shell, not docs template.** The
privacy policy is a standalone legal / policy page, not part of the
AIDE documentation. The docs template's left sidebar exists to navigate
between related doc sections — there is nothing to navigate on a
single-page policy. The marketing shell (`TopBar` + `Footer`, no
sidebar) matches how other top-level public pages are rendered and
keeps the policy visually equivalent to a "home-adjacent" page rather
than a doc leaf. Implementor uses the marketing `TopBar` and marketing
`Footer` (NOT `DocsFooter`), consistent with the root route.

**Content tone: engineering-credible, not legalese.** The root
intent names the target audience as "founders, operators, and technical
leaders who care about systems that work, not hype" (inherited from
the global brand posture). A boilerplate legal template would
contradict that positioning. The policy body is short declarative
sentences, specific claims, no hedging.

**Indexable, not noindexed.** The page is public and should appear in
search results — a site that publishes a privacy policy but hides it
from crawlers reads as performative. `/privacy` is added to the
sitemap (via §14) and carries no `robots.index:false`.

### Deviations NOT flagged

The following were observed during the audit but are NOT drift:

1. **`<img>` instead of `next/image` for Expo sprites and docs promo
   cards.** The root `next.config.mjs` sets `images: { unoptimized: true }`
   because the site is statically exported to GitHub Pages, which has no
   image-optimizer server. `<img>` is the correct choice and the existing
   `eslint-disable` comments document the exemption. No change.
2. **`<pre aria-label="Framework description">` in the Hero** — decorative-
   looking but carries meaningful prose; the aria-label gives it a SR name.
   Leave as-is.
3. **TrafficLights dots as decorative `<span>`s with `aria-hidden="true"`.**
   Window-chrome decoration, not interactive. Correct per seo.md ARIA
   Rules.
4. **`AsciiDivider` with `role="separator"` + `aria-hidden="true"`.**
   Idiomatic separator treatment; both attributes justified.
5. **`<html lang="en">`.** Already set. No action.
6. **Existing `<main>` landmarks on `/`, `/docs/**`, and `/not-found`.**
   All three routes already render `<main>`; this plan only adds
   `id="main"` for skip-link targeting.
7. **Root `metadata.openGraph` and `metadata.twitter`.** Already wired from
   `socialShare/ogImage` in layout.tsx; the closed `.aide` spec at
   `src/service/socialShare/.aide` defines the contract. Docs leaves
   inherit the image and card values per Next.js metadata merging — that
   `.aide` explicitly documents the inheritance pattern. Not re-audited.
8. **Canonical tags on `/docs/**` routes.** Each docs route sets
   `alternates.canonical` in its own metadata already; this audit only
   adds the missing root-route canonical plus removes the redundant
   client-side `CanonicalTag` component.
9. **Custom scrollbar CSS.** Already handled universally in globals.css
   (prior QA loop); no a11y gap.
10. **Reduced-motion support.** `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)`
    is already in globals.css. No change.
11. **Focus-visible ring.** Already styled via `:focus-visible` in
    globals.css with a 2px accent outline. No change.

### Out-of-scope recommendations

These are real improvements but too broad for a conformance refactor;
flag each as a follow-up task:

- **Breadcrumb semantics.** Refactor `DocsTemplate/Breadcrumb/index.tsx` to
  emit `<nav aria-label="Breadcrumb"><ol>...</ol></nav>` with each segment
  as `<li>` and the active segment marked `aria-current="page"`. Touches
  every docs page header. The current rendering is readable; the gap is
  "could be better labelled for screen-reader landmark navigation." Safe to
  defer.
- **`<time>` elements for DocMeta dates.** seo.md lists `<time dateTime>`
  as the semantic element; DocMeta currently renders `published` in a
  `<div>`. Minor, low priority.
- **Focus trap inside the docs sidebar drawer.** WCAG 2.4.3 for modal
  dialogs. Larger scope (needs a focus-trap utility or refactor to Radix
  Dialog); the Escape-key handler in §15 covers the most common dismissal
  path, which is sufficient for this refactor.
- **WebSite `potentialAction` / SearchAction.** Would enable Google's
  sitelinks-search-box for aidemd.dev. Marketing-level SEO, not on-page
  conformance — out of scope.
- **Color contrast tooling.** The contrast miss on `--color-dim-2` as body
  text would have been caught by `eslint-plugin-jsx-a11y` or an automated
  contrast linter. Consider adding the plugin project-wide and extending
  the playbook tooling section.

### Why this scope and not more

The user's brief was "how deep does the playbook normally go on on-page
SEO" and "do all we can" meaning playbook-deep, not gold-plated. Steps
1–15 close every gap the playbook mandates plus the Lighthouse-≥95-
implicit WCAG AA items; step 16 verifies. Anything beyond — Breadcrumb
refactor, `<time>` elements, focus trap, SearchAction, contrast linter —
exceeds "playbook-deep" and is deferred.
